If youâ€™re using a Kendo Grid with AJAX binding, you can tap into its error event or use the promise .fail() handler to show the Kendo Notification.

Example:

function onSave(e) {
    e.preventDefault();

    $.ajax({
        type: "POST",
        url: "/YourController/CreateScPartsUsedInEstimates?id=" + estimateId + "&gridType=" + gridType,
        data: new FormData($("#yourForm")[0]),
        processData: false,
        contentType: false
    })
    .done(function (response) {
        showNotification("Success", response, "success");
        // optionally refresh grid or reset form
    })
    .fail(function (xhr) {
        showNotification("Error", xhr.responseText, "error");
    });
}

function showNotification(title, message, type) {
    var notification = $("#notification").kendoNotification({
        stacking: "down",
        autoHideAfter: 5000,
        templates: [{
            type: "error",
            template: "<div class='error-notification'><strong>#= title #:</strong> #= message #</div>"
        }, {
            type: "success",
            template: "<div class='success-notification'><strong>#= title #:</strong> #= message #</div>"
        }]
    }).data("kendoNotification");

    notification.show({ title: title, message: message }, type);
}


And make sure youâ€™ve got a notification container somewhere on your page:

<div id="notification"></div>

ðŸ”’ Preventing Other Changes

If you want to block the user from continuing when thereâ€™s an error, you can disable certain UI elements when the error shows.
For example:

.fail(function (xhr) {
    showNotification("Error", xhr.responseText, "error");
    $("#saveButton, .k-grid-save-changes").prop("disabled", true);
});


You can later re-enable them when appropriate (e.g., after fixing inputs).
